title: For Sale:  Mauser 66 Rifle
location: wetsern Platte County, Missouri, United States
postcontent: I've had this Mauser 66 in .308 for about 10 years. It has a great, nicely figured piece of walnut on it with checkering that is close to perfect, if not perfect. It was a safe queen when I got it and stayed one. The previous owner had the barrel glass bedded which caused a slight gap between the receiver in the rear and the stock (pictured). My plan had been to unglass bed it, as previous Model 66s that I have owned shot well enough as configured by the factory. The previous owner also had a strange one piece wedge piece as a scope base in the front that I removed. Both scope rings would have fit on this base with that single barrel point of contact…that will do nothing for accuracy. Probably why the last owner had it glass bedded?? When the new buyer decides on his/her scope mounting system, that wedge vacancy will be invisible…or a wedge can be procured to be placed back in that area. These are the only two issues that I bring to your attention and they are IMHO pretty minor. The recoil pad has been professionally replaced, and if you know Mauser 66s this wil not surprise you. The bore is excellent as is the stock minus a couple handling dings. I do not believe this rifle has ever seen the field...and has only seen a range infrequently. Those minor issues above place this rifle at hundreds below other Mauser 66s.

title: For Sale:  Japanese Type 99 Arisaka
postcontent:
Considering selling this and moving it to a new home, make room for something else I've been fancying.
Japanese Type 99 rifle in the 7.7 Japanese caliber. From my research it was produced at the Toya Kogyo factory built sometime between 1939-1945. The mum is ground and it has the provisions for the anti-aircraft sight wings, but no wings (very likely it never had them). As is common, the bolt is mismatched. No indication of stock refinish that I can tell.
Chrome-lined bore is in excellent shape with sharp, clean rifling. The picture doesn't do justice to how bright it is, but you can tell it's sharp.
I've shot it and it shoots great. This is NOT a last-ditch rifle, perhaps a mid-war due to the AA sights being removed.

title: For Sale:  Remington Model 10 Shotgun
postcontent: For sale here is a rare and exemplary example of John Pedersen's designed Remington Model 10 shotgun.  Look like Eliot Ness while turning heads at the range.  Bottom feeding, bottom ejecting, and the bore looks like a mirror.  Awesome piece of history. fits 5 in the tube, 2 3/4 inch chamber.  This model served alongside the M1897 and Model 12 as World War I trench shotguns.  I have had some difficulty tracing the serial number, it appears it came before Remington's implementation of their modern serial number system.  Although it is close (or over) 100 years old, it still looks and fires great. I run Z-Max 00 Buck out of it all the time with no issues. Getting rid of it to please the Mrs.  Barrel has been chopped (prior to my ownership) to 18.5 inches. No bead on the end, but the aesthetics create a natural point of aim right down the barrel.  The absolute coolest feature of this gun is that it breaks down in half.  The original "violin case" shotgun.  There are only a few videos on Youtube concerning this shotgun, but all demonstrate its concealability when disassmebled. Kill two birds with one stone and own a piece of history and a reliable home defense weapon.Will consider trades, make an offer, but cash preferred.  $300 OBO.  Three3Zero 3Five2 Three3EightZero. Call or text.

title: For Sale:  Mauser 66 Rifle, .308
location: Western Platte County, Missouri, United States
postcontent: I've had this exceptional Mauser 66 in .308 for about a dozen years. It has a nicely figured piece of walnut with checkering that is close to perfect. It was a safe queen when I got it and stayed one. The previous owner had the barrel glass bedded which caused a slight gap between the receiver in the rear and the stock. My plan had been to unglass bed it to correct that, as previous Model 66s that I have owned shot well enough as configured by the factory. The previous owner also had a strange one piece wedge piece as a scope base in the front that I removed. Both scope rings would have fit on this base with that single barrel point of contact…that will do nothing for accuracy. Maybe why the last owner had it glass bedded?? When the new buyer decides on his/her scope mounting system, that wedge area vacancy behind the rear sight will be invisible…or a metal wedge can be procured to be placed back in that area. These are the only two issues and IMHO are pretty minor. Bore is excellent as is the stock, minus a couple mild handling dings. I do not believe this rifle has ever seen the field...and has only seen a range infrequently. Those minor issues above is why I have priced this rifle at hundreds below other Mauser 66s you will find. I can only post one picture, so if you want more, email me. I will ship in a hard case after I get an FFL to know where to send it. Shipping will be $40. Any questions, send me an email. Rob, US Army (Ret)

The manual safety is a thumb activated ambidextrous safety lever (up for SAFE, down for FIRE). The slide locks back after the last shot and a manual slide lock lever is also provided. The light, crisp trigger pull and fiber optic sights make the PMR-30 ideal for target shooting and hunting small game.Slide and barrel are 4140 steel, frame is 7075 aluminum. Grip, slide cover, trigger, mag release, and safety levers are glass reinforced Nylon (Zytel), much like other Kel-Tec Pistols. Magazine is Also Zytel and holds 30 rounds, with round count ports. Other features include: dual opposing extractors for reliability, heel magazine release to aid in magazine retention, dovetailed aluminum front sight, Picatinny accessory rail under the barrel, Urethane recoil buffer, captive coaxial recoil springs. PMR30 disassembles for cleaning by removal of a single pin.
